<div id="tab-methodology" class="tab-content">
  <div class="meth-wrap">
    <div style="margin-bottom:22px;">
      <div style="font-size:20px;font-weight:700;margin-bottom:6px;">Methodology</div>
      <div class="meth-text">Bloomberg-sourced weekly fundamental data for 56 MSCI country indices spanning Developed, Emerging, and Frontier markets, as of 6 March 2026.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="meth-card">
      <div class="meth-card-title" style="color:var(--accent2)">Cross-Sectional Z-Score</div>
      <div class="code-block">z_i = (x_i − μ_universe) / σ_universe</div>
      <div class="meth-text">Where <code>x_i</code> is current PE or P/B for market i; μ and σ are computed across all markets with valid data using <strong style="color:var(--text)">sample standard deviation</strong> (÷ N−1, Bessel-corrected). Outliers with PE&gt;100 are excluded. <strong style="color:var(--text)">Universe Z</strong> compares a market to the full global peer set. <strong style="color:var(--text)">Class Z</strong> compares within its own tier (Developed vs Developed, Emerging vs Emerging), which removes the structural valuation premium in DM over EM/FM.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="meth-card">
      <div class="meth-card-title" style="color:var(--gold2)">Rolling Time-Series Z-Score</div>
      <div class="code-block">z_t = (x_t − μ_{t−W:t}) / σ_{t−W:t}  (sample std, ÷ N−1)</div>
      <div class="meth-text">Rolling window of W weeks (default 52W). Measures how expensive a market is relative to its own recent history. Values above +2σ suggest extended valuations relative to recent history; below −2σ suggest historically cheap levels. <strong style="color:var(--text)">Important:</strong> this is a mean-reversion signal, not a timing tool.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="meth-card">
      <div class="meth-card-title" style="color:var(--green2)">Trailing / Forward PE Premium</div>
      <div class="code-block">disc = (trailing_PE / fwd_PE − 1) × 100%</div>
      <div class="meth-text">Positive values mean the market trades at a premium to consensus forward estimates — i.e. earnings are expected to grow. Large positive values (e.g. South Korea +154%) indicate aggressive earnings-growth expectations priced in. Negative values mean earnings are expected to contract.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="meth-card">
      <div class="meth-card-title" style="color:var(--purple2)">Log Z-Score (Spike-Robust Mode)</div>
      <div class="code-block">z_t = (log(x_t) − μ_log) / σ_log</div>
      <div class="meth-text">When <strong style="color:var(--text)">Log Z</strong> mode is active, the z-score is computed on the natural logarithm of the valuation series rather than the raw values. This compresses large upward spikes (e.g. PE ratios during earnings collapses or thin market periods) that would otherwise inflate the rolling standard deviation and cause the linear z-score to systematically understate how expensive or cheap a market is in calmer periods. The back-transformed rolling mean and band displayed on the raw-value chart uses the log-normal expectation <code>exp(μ_log + σ_log²/2)</code>. Raw PE/P/B values are always displayed unchanged; only the z-score computation operates in log-space.</div>
    </div>
      <div class="meth-text" style="line-height:2;">
        <div><span style="color:var(--text)">Indices:</span> MSCI total return (net dividends, USD) · Bloomberg ticker format: [code] Index</div>
        <div><span style="color:var(--text)">Frequency:</span> Weekly Friday close</div>
        <div><span style="color:var(--text)">Fields:</span> PX_LAST · PE_RATIO · BEST_PE_RATIO (consensus fwd) · PX_TO_BOOK_RATIO · PROF_MARGIN</div>
        <div><span style="color:var(--text)">History:</span> Available from 1995 · varies by market</div>
        <div><span style="color:var(--text)">Note on Estonia (PE 54.5x):</span> Retained as a genuine outlier but visible in chart; drives the cross-sectional std slightly higher.</div>
      </div>
    <div class="meth-card">
      <div class="meth-card-title" style="color:var(--accent2)">Price Index &amp; Signal Bands</div>
      <div class="code-block">Signal: shade where combined_Z &gt; +&sigma; (overvalued) or &lt; &minus;&sigma; (undervalued)</div>
      <div class="meth-text">The <strong style="color:var(--text)">Historical Price Index</strong> chart overlays valuation signals on the price series. Signal bands use the <strong style="color:var(--text)">combined Z-score</strong> — the average of PE Z and P/B Z at each point. Green bands = periods both metrics were historically cheap; red bands = stretched valuations. Threshold is selectable at ±1σ, ±2σ, or ±3σ. Price is plotted on a <strong style="color:var(--text)">log scale</strong> to preserve legibility across multi-decade series.</div>
    </div>


    <div class="meth-card">
      <div class="meth-card-title" style="color:var(--red2)">Signal Interpretation</div>
